{ Of the 4 options that the white player has, 3. e5 is slightly the most common of all. }
3. e5 { In this position, Black has three possibilities:
1. c5, the Botvinnik-Carls Defense;
2. Bf5;
3. g6;
Play 3. c5. } { [%cal Gg7g6,Gc6c5,Gc8f5] } 3... c5 { White defend the d4 Pawn playing c3. This variation is called "Botvinnik-Carls Defense". } 4. c3 { White's player builds a solid structure of pawns aiming at the kingside, it is probably in that sector that his opponent will want to attack.
Develop your Knight to the c6 square to press the d4 pawn } { [%cal Gb2e5] } 4... Nc6 { White plays Nf3 to add an additional defender for e5 and d5 Pawns. } 5. Nf3 { Capture his pawn. } 5... cxd4 { White capture the Black Pawn in d4. } 6. cxd4 { Where is the best development square for our Black Bishop? } 6... Bg4 { Excellent! It is a similar position to the Advance Variation of the French Defense, but you have the advantage that the light-squared bishop is free and not blocked. } *


